Hit Refresh: The Quest to Rediscover Microsoft's Soul and Imagine a Better Future for Everyone by Satya Nadella

Book description: Hit Refresh is the story of corporate change and reinvention as well as the story of Nadella’s personal journey, one that is taking place today inside a storied technology company, and one that is coming in all of our lives as intelligent machines become more ambient and more ubiquitous. It’s about how people, organizations and societies can and must hit refresh—transform—in their persistent quest for new energy, new ideas, relevance and renewal. At the core, it’s about us humans and our unique qualities, like empathy, which will become ever more valuable in a world where the torrent of technology will disrupt like never before. As much a humanist as a technologist, Nadella defines his mission and that of the company he leads as empowering every person and every organization on the planet to achieve more. As much a humanist as a technologist, Nadella defines his mission and that of the company he leads as empowering every person and every organization on the planet to achieve more.

Review: Being an opensource enthusiast, the guys from opensource and Linux world has always despised Microsoft, we have been into the era of the wars of silicon valley and witnessed their struggle to reach to the top position to rule the game field.

this is the story of how microsoft has transioned itself from a propritory compay to now a fierce supporter of open source. how Microsoft has started to change in the technology adaoption and becoming better at it, despite the leaders of those technologies still are the leading force.

In this book and the initial 3 chapters, Satya Nadella speaks about his fascinating childhood before immigrating to the U.S. and how he learned to lead along the way and shares his meditations as a sitting CEO—one who is mostly unknown following the brainy Bill \
Gates and Steve Ballmer.

from chapter 4 to the next 9 chapters He tells the inside story of how a company rediscovered its soul—transforming everything from culture to their fiercely competitive landscape and industry partnerships.

The author has shown his willingness to embrace change by forging new partnerships with companies long-viewed as arch rivals such as Red Hat and Apple and acquiring new platforms promising growth opportunities. The compnay has made acquisitons as popular game Minecraft, the developer platform Github, and the social network LinkedIn which shows how microsoft has successfully repositioned itself—going from a “devices and services” company to a “mobile and cloud” company.

During the last chapters the author focuses on three technologies that lead to massive shifts in the economy and society: mixed reality, artificial intelligence and quantum computing. The first changes how people interface with computing and the digital world by increasing the experiential nature of the specific task.

At the end of the book Nadella reprises a theme he sees as a core value in creating successful relationships for employees, managers, partners and people in general: the importance of education and empathy. Education as an essential road to understanding and using new technology so that a knowledge gap does not create further displacement in society.

As Nadella explains “Ideas excite me, Empathy grounds and centers me.” Hit Refresh is a set of reflections, meditations, and recommendations presented as algorithms from a principled, deliberative leader searching for improvement—for himself, for a storied company, and for society.

Empathy is critical for leaders and managers to understand others, their motives, wants and needs. 

